019s Commentary CBS\n2:00\u2014Stars Concert With Barlow\u2014NBC\nTo Be Announced (30 Min.) CBS\nSongs Period; String Quartet ABC\nChaplain Jim, U.S.A.. Drama MBS\n2:30\u2014John Charles Thomas Song NBC\nHollywood Star Time Theater CBS\nSunday Vespers via the Radio ABC\nBill Cunningham in Comment MBS\n2:45\u2014Symphonic Strings (15 m.)\u2014MBS\n3-00\u2014Parade ofMusic, Max Hill\u2014NBC\nN. Y. Philadelphia Symphony CBS\nElmer Davis in a Commentary ABC\nSongs From Along the Trail MBS\n3:15\u2014The Galen Drake Program ABC\n3:30\u2014One Man's Family, Drama NBC\nThis Week Around the World ABC\nTo Be Announced (30 Mins.) MBS\n4:00\u2014National Forum Guests NBC\nTo Be Announced\u2014ABC-New England\n1 Darts for Dough, a Quiz\u2014other ABC\nMurder Is My Hobby, Mystery MBS\n4:30\u2014Sunday Matinee in Variety NBC\nNelson Eddy Concert Guests\u2014CBS\nMary Small in a Sunday Revue\u2014ABC\nDetective Mysteries via Radio MBS\n5:00\u2014NBC Symphony Orchestra NBC\nFamily Time Patrice Munsel CBS\nJones and I, a Safety Drama ABC\nThe Shadow Mystery Series MBS\n5:30\u2014Gene Autry Song Show CBS\nTo Be Announced (30 Mins.) ABC\nNick Carter, Detective Drama MBS\n5:45\u2014Bill Shirer in Commentary CBS\n6:00\u2014The Catholic Radio Service NBC\nAdventures of Ozzie Harriet CBS\nHall of Fame. Paul Whiteman ABC\nQuick As a Flash in a Quiz MBS\n6:30\u2014G-eat Gildersleeve Comedy NBC\nTl,., Dohv Crimea,, QVinu; _ CRS\nSunday Evening Party Music ABC\nCedric Fester His Comment MBS\n6:45\u2014Fulton Lewis. Jr., Com\u2019nt MBS\n7:00\u2014Jack Benny Comedy Show NBC\nAdventures With the Thin Man CBS\nDrew Perrson and Commentary ABC\nOpinion Requested, Servicemen MBS\n7:15\u2014News Summary for 15 Min.\u2014ABC\n7:30\u2014The Bandwagon Broadcast\u2014NBC\nBlondie-Dagwood Comedy Skit CBS\nQuiz Kids and Joe Kelly M.C.\u2014ABC\nCalifornia Melodies by Orches. MBS\n8:00\u2014Chas. McCarthy Bergen NBC\nMarlin Hurt\u2019s Beulah Comedy CBS\nThe Sunday Evening Symphony ABC\nAlexander Mediation Board\u2014MBS\n8:30\u2014Fred Allen\u2019s Comedy Gang NBC\nCrime Doctor, Dramatic Series CBS\nDon\u2019t Be a Sucker, Dramatic MBS\n8:45\u2014Gabriel Heatter Comment MBS\n8:55\u2014Five Minutes News Period CBS\n9:00\u2014Sunday\u2019s Merry Go Round\u2014NBC\nRequest Performance by Guests\u2014CBS\nWalter Winchell Broadcasting ABC\nExporing Unknown in Science MBS\n9:15\u2014Commentary on Hollywood ABC\n9:30\u2014Album of Familiar Music NBC\nEd Wynn With James Melton CBS\nLa Guardia\u2019s Sunday Comment ABC\nDouble or Nothing in a Quiz MBS\n9:45\u2014Jimmy Fidler\u2019s Hollywood ABC\n10:00\u2014Phil Spitalny Girl Orch. NBC\nPhil Baker\u2019s Take It or Leave It\u2014CBS\nTheater Guild\u2019s Drama Hour ABC\nFreedom of Opportunity, Drama\u2014MBS\n10:30\u2014Meet Me at Parky\u2019s Now\u2014NBC\nWe, the People, a Guest Show CBS\nWhat\u2019s Name of the Song Quiz MBS\n11:00\u2014Variety and News (2 hr.) NBC\nNews, Variety; Dance (2 h.)\u2014CBS-ABC\nComment Dance Bands (2 h.)\u2014MBS\nRoxas Nominated For\nPhilippine Presidency\nMANILA, Jan. 19\u2014 UR\u2014Manuel\nRoxas, was nominated for the presi\ndency of the Philippines today by\nthe Liberal wing of the Nation\nalista party and immediately ac\ncepted in a speech critical of Presi\ndent Segio Osmenna, who will be\nhis opponent in the April election.\nRoxas and Osmena, long friends\n#nd political allies, finally split\n\u2022fficially last month. Osmena is\nregarded as the certain choice ol\nthe Regular wing of the Nacion\nalista party at its nominating con\n\u25bcentio nnext Monday. A proposal\nthat Roxas run for vice-president\non Osmena\u2019s ticket failed. in De\ncember.\nGIs AID TYPHUS TEST\nFORT LEWIS. Wash. (U.R)\u2014One\nhundred and fifty medical train\ning section soldiers recently sub\njected themselves to a two-week\nexperiment to determine whethei\nclothing impregnated with dibuty]\nphthalate and benzyl benzoate,\nused to repel the mite carrying\nscrub typhus fever virus, would\ncase skin irritation.\nResults were highly satisfactory,\naccording to an offial, and not\n\u00a9le case of skin irritation re\nsulted from the experiment.\nSENSATIONAL BARGAIN\nfor Short Tlmo Only.,.\nThis MBianf low price brings yon 200,\nhealthy 1st year sire bulblets at a price\nalmost unheard of before! Varieties\nnormally priced to sell for (6 to\n$10 in older bulbs! Beautiful\nRainbow Mix to give your gar\nden a riot of color! Sent in time\nfor spring planting with full\nmoney back guarantee! Order\nnow! SEND NO MONEY \u2014Just\ni name and address; pay postman\nonly $1.49 plus C.O.D. postage\n1 on arrival (cash orders sent prepaid). Mail order\nTODAY to gst.tlO# special jpfferJ Send to\nMICHIGAN BULB CO.,\nDept. A-736, Grand Sapid, 2, Michigan\nComforts Of Home On The Picket Line\nTwo pickets relax in asy chairs in front of a g ate to the strike-bound plant of the Bethlehem Steel\ncompany at Lackawanna, N. Y., as a fellow picket tries to coax a little more heat out of a salamander\nwhile biting winds from Lake Erie whistle overhead. The other men also are pickets. The strike at the\nplant has kept 11,000 workers idle for nearly a week.__\nOver The Airways\n\u2014By BEN McDonald\nIn an effort to enlist the full\ncooperation of the business firms\nin Wilmington and vicinity in the\ncurrent veterans\u2019 problems, the\nNew Hanover chapter, No. 11, Am\nerican War Dads, recently voted\nto defray a part of the expense of\na radio program presented each\nweek over WMFD in the interest\nof the returning serviceman.\nThe local chapter of the Wdr\nDads, a non-political, non-sectarian\nand non-profit organization, was\nformed several months ago \u201cto aid\nour returning sons and daughters\nin their re-employment problems,\neconomic needs and in their post\nwar rehabilitation program.\u201d At\nthat time the members elected W.\nL. Sheffield, president; J. B. Ed\nwards, vice president; C. L. Myers,\nsecretary and Clayton C. Holmes,\ntreasurer.\nLOOKING BACK\nWHEN\u2014the local radio station\u2019s\ncall letters were adopted as the re\nsult of a popular local vote, to wit,\nWRBT\u2014\u201cWonderful Resort-Beauti\nful Town\u201d By the way, WMFD;\nmeans \u201cWe Make Friends Daily.\u201d\nMrs. Carlton Newtons (Dora Baker)\nniorift nlnwinrt m onv nrn.\ngrams Sigmund Spaeth wowed\nthe town with a personal appear\nance The vocals of John Curtis\nrecently discharged, were so lis\ntenable The sweet organ play\ning of Mrs. Jere Holmes (Mary B.\nWilliams) tickled the ears Wes\nton Britt, now in Montgomery, Ala.,\nwas the tops in program direction\nin these here parts Amos Allen,\nnow out of the service, beat it out\non the keys Andrew Murray\nwas the first person to broadcast\nlocally. Incidently, Murray got his\nArmy discharge December 1\u2014and\nis now working in St. Ijouis.\nIN PASSING\nMy wife tells me I\u2019m in the wrong\nand of this radio busines, I should\nbe in the producing end, sez, she\nat least \u201cproducing\u201d a program\nlike \u201cLadies, Be Seated\u201d. And by\nthe way what woman wouldn\u2019t get\nexcited over a program that gives\naway a major electric appliance\nevery day in the week and once a\nweek clothes some lucky woman\nin the swankiest fashion ensemble\nthis side of Hattie Carnegie.\nHere\u2019s the way it works out:\nEvery day, Monday through Fri\nday, on WMFD at 3:30 p.m. \u201cLadies\nbe Seated,\u201d an iron, radio, wash\ning machine, etc., is given away to\nthe woman who that day sends in\nthe best set of questions to be asked\nof participating guests on the \"In\nquiring Reporter\u201d portion of the\nprogram. And that\u2019s not all. Every\nMonday the woman judged to be the\nbest vocalist on the program during\nthe proceeding week is awarded a\ncomplete clothing ensemble from\nthe swankies fashion houses in\nNew York. So put this down in your\nlittle blue book, Ladies, and when\nyou get into New York try out your\nluck on the program.\nWHERE ARE THEY\nAll members of the former Belk\nWilliams quartet, which was under\na rli\u2019rop+inn n-f Willinm T7aKai4\nson, with the exception of D. If.\nBuie, are still in Wilmington. W. G.\nRobertson is the organist at St.\nJames\u2019 Episcopal church Ar\nthur John is a singer at St. An\ndrews Covenant Presbyterian\nchurch. W. A. Kamer, the optician,\nstill has his place of business on\nFront Street.\nSPOT NEWS\nIt\u2019s new\u2014It\u2019s different\u2014It\u2019s THE\nSTAR-NEWS\u2019 Newsreel. Yes, my\nfriends, something new in local ra\ndio presentation has been added\nand will be delivered to you via\nyour radio set at 1:15 p. m. today\nover WMFD. Always in the van,\nthe Star-News brings you your\nRound The Town Reporter in a\ntimely, lively program which con\ncerns you, and you and you. The\nTIME\u20141:15 p. m. The station,\nWMFD.\nLISTENING POST\nOverheard in the bus: \u201cWhy not\nlet the High school kids put a play\non the radio once in a while\u2019\u2019 If you\nlike jungle stuff, don\u2019t miss the\nTheatre Guild show tonight\nJimmie Gleason has a record of 15\nyears of soldiering both as an en\nlisted man and an officer Tom\nmy Wells, who did a number of the\nCamp Davis shows, is now announc\ning in Boston when Joe Kelly\nasked the Quiz Kids how they\nwould entertain young children they\ngave a variety of answers but\npint-sized Richard Weixler, age 5,\ntvho was the age the other kids were\nreferring to, piped up \u201cI would\nplay a game with a somewhat\nsmaller child\u201d Johnnie Sellers\nhas heard from NBC and his\nchances for a job with the network\nlook good. Jack Johnson has cer\ntainly improved the sounds effects\nand his choice of records are really\ngood\u2014Jack is production man out\nat WMFD.\nAND\nListen to your Star-News Round\nthe Town Reporter with spot news\nat 1:25 p. m. and 6:25 p. m. Mon\nday through Saturday.\nAIRPLANE DEALER\nFRANCHISE LISTED\nCarolina Skyway*, operating\nfrom Peiffer field on the Wrights\nville Beach road, has been award\ned the Fairchild dealership for\nNew Hanover county and sur\nrounding territory by Tom Davis,\nPiedmont aviation, Winston-Salem,\nwhich holds the state distributor\nship, according to information r#\nceived here yesterday.\nAn order has been placed for a\nplane, scheduled for delivery the\nfirst week in March.\nAnother aircraft, the new Aer\nonca Champion, already has ar\nrived at the field'. A post-war\nmodel, the plane evidences engi\nneering advancements achieved by\nAeronca Aircraft corporation dur\ning four years of manufacturing\nfor the Army and Navy. The com\npany received -an Army-Navy\naward for efficiency.\nLaurens Man Heads\nPalmetto Publishers\nCOLUMBIA, S. 9., Jan. 19.\u2014UR\u2014\nEditor and Publisher Allison Lee\nof the Laurens Advertiser was in\nstalled as president of the South\nCarolina Press Association today\nas it ended its annual two-day mid\nwinter institute.\nPublisher J. M. Blalock of the\nstate and the Columbia record was\nadvanced to the vice presidency\nand B. J. King of the Aiken Stand\n3TH aVlfl T? QTTiom Tiro p irl/Tfl\npresident.\nA luncheon address on the ma\nchinery of conducting polls was\ndelivered by W. J. Gaskill, an as\nsociate editor of the Gallup Poll,\nwhen illness prevented poll di\nrector George W. Gallup from ap\npearing.\nNew Paper Products\nFirm Begins Operation\nWith Headquarters Hen\nThe Cape Fear Paper Products\ncompany, 1121 South Front street\nhas begun operations in easterr\nNorth Carolina, it was announced\nyesterday by L. H. Welsh, mana\nger.\nThe company will distribute,\nWelsh said, all kinds of paper pro\nducts including paper bags, cups,\nprinted cellophane bags, facial tis\nsue, paper boxes and toilet tissue.\nWelsh and his brother organized\nthe company in the fall of 1945.\nTwo Religious Films\nScheduled For Showing\nAt First Advent Church\nTwo religious sound films will\nbe shown at the First Advent\nChristian church, 504 S. Sixth\nstreet, tonight at 7:30 o\u2019clock, it\nwas announced yesterday by the\nRev. James R. Lee, pastor.\nOne of the films is made up of\nfour five-minute messages by Dr.\nOswald J. Smith, Dr. Walter Wil\nson, Dr. W. B. Riley and Dr. H. A.\nIronside on the topic, \u201cFive Min\nutes to Live.\u201d The other film is\nan exposition on Bible promise^\nReturned Army Uthcer\nResumes Law Practice\nAddison Hewlett, Jr., has re\nsumed his law practice in Wil\nmington and now occupies new of\nfices on the second floor of the\nOdd' Fellows building, Third and\nPrincess streets.\nHewlett has recently been sepa\nrated from the Army after three\nand one-half years\u2019 service, both\nin this country and with the 38th\nBombardment group in the South\nern and Western Pacific.\nBy act of Congress, the govern\nment moved into Washington on the\nfirst Monday in December, 1800.\nWITH YOUR\nROUND-THE-TOWN REPORTER\nBen McDonald\nI\n\nI\nN. C. Press Will Receive First Hand\nReport On Big Reconversion Problems\n___ T\u201c\nTop-Ranking Federal Of\nficials To Attend Chap\nel Hill Meeting\nCHAPEL HILL, Jan. 19.\u2014North\nCarolina newspaper men and wo\nmen will have an opportunity next\nweek to hear, first-hand, accounts\nand opinions of the nation\u2019s handl\ning of its reconversion problems\n_problems about which they have\nbeen writing for pnany months.\nTwo top-ranking government of\nficials and one internationally\nknown newspaper publisher are\nthe principal speakers on the pro\ngram of the mid-winter North Car\nolina Newspaper Institute to be\nheld at Chapel Hill and Durham\nnext week, Thursday and Friday,\nJanuary 24-25.\nFred M. Vinson, Secretary of\nthe Treasury, and W. R. Davhn,\nExecutive Secretary of the War\nMobilization and Reconversion Ad\nvisory Board, which was formerly\ndirected by Secretary Vinson, will\nspeak at the Chapel Hill sessions,\nwhile Robert McLean, president\nof the Associated Press and presi\ndent and publisher of the Philadel\nphia Bulletin, will speak at a ses\nsion in Durham.\nThe Institute, which is sponsored\nby the North Carolina Press\nsociation with the cooperation of\nthe University of North Carolina\nand Duke University, \\yill open\nwith registration at the Carolina\nInn on Friday afternoon, January\n24.\nSecretary Vinson will give the\nopening address that night in Hill\nHall at 8 o\u2019clock. He will be in\ntroduced by former Governor O.\nMax Gardner, of Shelby, and\nWashington, chairman of the War\nMobilization and Reconversion\nAdvisory Board.\nIlr. Devlin, who has served un\nder the Gardner chairmanship of\nthe Board since it was put into\noperation a year ago, will speak\nat a luncheon session here Friday\nwith the University as host.\nSecretary Vinson, who is said\nnever to have \u201cwalked around a\nfight\u2014he always goes to the mid\ndle of it\u201d\u2014is popular with and\nhas the confidence of both Demo\ncrats and Republicans alike Al\nthough a New Dealer, he frequent\nly asserted his Independence and\nbucked both President Roosevelt\nand conservatives in Congress\nmore than one issue. H\nSecretary Vinson succeeded\nSecretary of State James\nByrnes as director of the\nWar Mobilization and Recover\nsion. He also directed the Office\nof Economic Stabilization before\nPresident Truman called on him\nt0 take over in place of Henry\nMorgenthau, Jr.\nA native of Louisa, Ky., a lit\ntle mountain village where his\nfather was jailer, Secretary Vin\nson graduated from Centre Col\nlege Danville, Ky., in 1909, and\nreceived his law degree two years\nlater. For eight years he was\nDistrict Attorney in Kentucky be\nfore he was fleeted to the House\nof Representatives where he re\nmained until 1937 except for two\nyears during the Hoover adminis\ntration.\nHe resigned in 1938 to become\nan associate justice of the U. S.\nCourt of Appeals for the District\nof Columbia. President Roosevelt\nnamed him director of Economic\nStabilization in 1943, a job calling\nfor \u2018\u2018a man with a thick hide,\u201d\na qualification Mr. Vinson would\nbe the last to admit he lacked.\nEarly in 1945 he was nominated\nby President Roosevelt to suc\nceed Jesse Jones as Federal\nLoan administrator. The Senate\nconfirmed his appointment to head\nthe $40,000,000,000 Reconstruction\nFinance corporation and its allied\nagencies. It was shortly after\nward that Mr. Byrnes resigned\nfrom the Office of War Mobiliza\ntion and Reconversion and Mr.\nVinson was called to succeed him.\nMr. Devlin, as executive secre\ntary of the board, has to deal with\ntop policy matters in the reconver\nsion program\u2014price and wage\ncontrols, surplus disposal, mate\nrials, shortages, housing, the\nchange-over of industrial plants to\npeace production, veterans pro\ngrams, business and employment\nprospects.\nA native of Atlanta, Mr. Devlin\nreceived a medical discharge from\nthe Army in 1944 after serving two\nyears in the Quartermaster Corps.\nA graduate of economics from the\nUniversity of Wisconsin, he spent\ntwo years, beginning in 1936, with\nthe Tennessee Valley Authority\nwhere he was engaged in research\non problems of agricultural and\nindustrial development. In 1939\nhe joined the research staff of the\nNational Resources Planning\nBoard under Frederic Delano.\nIn 1940, Mr. Devlin became re\ngional director of the southern re\ngional office of th'e National\nResources Planning Board in At\nlanta and Executive Secretary of\nthe Southeastern Regional Plan\nning Commission. In these capaci\nties he organized and directed a\nresearch program concerned with\ndevelopment possibilities in south\nern business, agriculture, forestry,\nwater resources, transportation,\nhealth, education and housing. The\nmajor studies and recommenda\ntions growing out of this program\nwere brought together in a report\nof the Southeastern Regional Plan\nning Commission, published by the\nNational Regional Planning Board\nas \u201cRegional Planning in the\nUnited States,'Part XI, The South\neast.\u201d\nRobert McLean, who has been\npresident of the Associated Press\nsince 1938, has followed in his\nfather\u2019s footsteps as president and\npublisher of the Evening Bulletin\nand also as a director for many\nyears of the AP.\nA native of Philadelphia, he at\ntended schools conducted by the\nGET quick relief with krey,\nmodem, fast-acting remedr toj\ncoughs due to colds. KREY fjj,\nnature to heal sore merahrmei\nhelps to open the air\nGet KREY at your o.\ntoday!\nASK FOR\nSociety of Friends in. the r H\nBrotherly Love and -r tc 3;\nfrom Princeton .qn\u2018'\"\u2018a\nceived an honorary ri<..,.''ef r Vs' V\ntor of Laws from- F-y 3 I\nMarshall College. i I\nHe succeeded his father 1\nof the Evening Bullet--\nto have the largest e\\'enj* S5:i I\nculation of any paper m th? c4- I\ntry. in 1931. His fatnw- -C >1\nL. McLean, had been a direr. 51 I\nthe AP since its forrna*ion Cl0:'; H\nand Robert McLean succeed^ I\nthat position in 1924. He Q I\nthe Board of Directors re\u201e ,:I\nsince, becoming vice i resiHU'\u00b0:- I\n1936, and president in 1938 \u00b0ea'4 I\nTwo Building Permits f\nIssued Here Yesterday I\nTotalled Above $20,0(1) I\nMike Patellis, owner of the p I\nous GriU, Carolina Beach\nyesterday was issued a perm^'l\nenlarge his establishment tj1 :s I\nmodel the front. Work. schedvJ\nto'begin immediately, is exD \u201cI\nto cost about $16,000\nGilber* F- Morton, city 1\nmg inspector, also granted k! I\nmission to Luther Jordan t0 K,'f\na one-story addition to be m'i\nas a dwelling adjacent to\nconnecting with his funeral hot\n306 South Seventh street at\nestimated cost of $4,500. 85\nCABBIE\u2019S RECORD BROKfy\nINDIANAPOLIS (U.R) ,_A\nhansom cab driver broke h f\nyear-old record of d r i v i n\nmotorized cab without an accil- -j\nrecently when his taxi colC- 1\nwith a truck. Fred Barber. 60 s~]\nit was the first accident for\nsince he began driving taxis\nIndianapolis in 1922.","height":"27484","width":"20560"}}
